Report on zonal TCM

Jiefeng Kang

2023-02-06

1 Introduction

In this report, I apply zonal travel cost model (TCM) to the 4 trailheads respectively, to explore the relationship between visitation rate and travel cost. The method mostly follows the methodology in the report 京都大学, 北海道大学, 甲南大学, 国立環境研究所, 2019. 我が国における自然環境施策への効果的な資源動員に向けた研究研究報告書.

2 Method

2.1 旅費計算

The travel cost was calculated as the transportation cost. I assume all the visitors go to the trail heads by car. The formula and assumptions are as follows.

\[TC_{ij} = D_{ij} \times E_{ij} \times P_{ij}\]

where \(i\) is the home prefecture; \(j\) is the target trail head; \(D\) is travel distance, which is assumed to be the best route between home prefecture \(i\) and the trail head \(j\); \(E\) is the gasoline efficiency is 21.7 km/L (according to 国土交通省, that is 平成26年度ガソリン乗用車のJC08モード燃費); \(P\) is price for gasoline is 126 Yen/L (according to 総務省’s investigation, that is 2016年7月~9月における静岡県のガソリン販売平均価格).

Of course there are some bugs. (1) The variables in the assumption should be updated, for example, updated to the values in 2018 and 2019. (2) Should include opportunity cost into travel cost. For example, the travel cost of a prefecture = transportation cost + opportunity cost, among which, opportunity cost = 1/3 * average income of the prefecture. (3) I didn’t include 高速道路利用料金 in the transportation cost. (4) It is not reasonable to assume that all visitors go to the trail heads by car. It makes sense to follow the previous report to assume that visitors from some prefectures go to Fujisan by flight first. The best practice is to extract the transportation mode of all the visitors. However, that is very challenging (I tried and reported the results before).

\[VR_{ijk} = V_{ijk} / P_{ik}\]

where \(i\) is the home prefecture; \(j\) is the target trail head; \(k\) is year (2018 or 2019); \(VR\) is the visitation rate (unit: /1000); \(V\) is the number of visitations = number of dailyid, here I assumes that the visitation turnover rate is 0; \(P\) is the population of the prefecture \(i\).

2.3 Model

Now we have got the dependent variable (visitation rate) and independent variable (travel cost), we can explore the relationship between them. I used linear model for the analysis. There are 4 choices based of the model:

\[VR = \alpha + \beta \times TC\] \[log(VR) = \alpha + \beta \times TC\] \[VR = \alpha + \beta \times log(TC)\] \[log(VR) = \alpha + \beta \times log(TC)\]

where VR is visitation rate, TC is travel cost. Again, I followed the report 京都大学, 北海道大学, 甲南大学, 国立環境研究所, 2019. 我が国における自然環境施策への効果的な資源動員に向けた研究研究報告書., used \(log(VR) = \alpha + \beta \times TC\) in this analysis.

The regression model was applied to the whole dataset and sub-dataset for each pair of home prefecture - trail head respectively.

However, for the methodology, there are some questions.

  1. For any statistical analysis, there are some assumptions (e.g., normal distribution), but I haven’t test the assumptions yet.

  2. When applying traditional statistical analysis to big data, there can be some problem. One of them is that the p value is likely to be always significant, and for big data, it could be more reasonable to focus on effect size at the same time (rather than just focus on p value, see “Big data studies can identify significant but inconsequential effects” section of Kaplan, R.M., Chambers, D.A., Glasgow, R.E., 2014. Big Data and Large Sample Size: A Cautionary Note on the Potential for Bias. Clinical and Translational Science 7, 342–346. https://doi.org/10.1111/cts.12178 for more details).
